			<h3 class="first"><a href="#p15509">Why do we need a Roomba for pets?</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=15509&amp;sid=4af85a60d89537be09274c45072d2d5e#p15509"><img src="./styles/robotreviews/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=2021&amp;sid=4af85a60d89537be09274c45072d2d5e">Dorktastic</a></strong> &raquo; September 8th, 2006, 2:08 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content">Why do we need a <a href="http://www.robotreviews.com/buy/roomba-532-pets" class="postlink-local">Roomba For Pets</a>?<br /><br />I'm going to betray my ignorance here:  I can't quite see why pet hair is such a challenge for Roomba.  <br /><br />I am imagining that you'd have to empty the dust bin constantly and the brushes would get hairy, if you had cats and dogs.  But I have 2 human roommates with long hair (one to her chin, one below her shoulders) and that seems like a much bigger threat to Roomba.  Hair winds around the brushes, under the side brush, into the brush bearing areas, into the wheels, etc.<br /><br />Isn't long human hair a lot worse for Roomba than pet tumblefur balls?  What am I missing?<br />Or should we have a Roomba for Long haired Humans?  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /></div>

			

		</div>

		
